Scopes:
Spring beans can have different scopes, which define how many instances of a bean Spring
creates and how they are shared.

Types:

a. Singleton (Default):
Definition: Only one instance per Spring container.
Usage: Most beans (stateless services, DAOs).
Example:

@Component
@Scope("singleton")
public class EmailService { }
Behavior: Every request for this bean returns the same instance.

b. Prototype:
Definition: A new instance is created every time the bean is requested.
Usage: For stateful beans or beans that need to be different for each use.
Example:

@Component
@Scope("prototype")
public class UserSession { }
Behavior: Each request gets a new instance.

c. Web-specific Scopes:
1.Request:
One bean per HTTP request.
Ex:

@Component
@Scope("request")
public class RequestBean { }

2.Session:
One bean per HTTP session.
Ex:

@Component
@Scope("session")
public class SessionBean { }

3.Application:
One bean per ServletContext (web app).
Ex:

@Component
@Scope("application")
public class AppBean { }

4.WebSocket:
One bean per WebSocket session.
Ex:

@Component
@Scope("websocket")
public class WebSocketBean { }

Note: Web scopes require a web-aware Spring ApplicationContext.


2. Difference Between HTTP Request and HTTP Session

HTTP Request:
Definition:
A single call from a client (browser, app, etc.) to the server, such as loading a page or submitting a form.
Scope:
Lasts only as long as the server is processing that one request.
Spring Scope:
Beans with @Scope("request") are created new for each HTTP request.
Example Use:
Tracking data for a single page load or form submission.

HTTP Session:
Definition:
A series of requests from the same user/client, grouped together by the server to maintain state (like login status) across multiple requests.
Scope:
Lasts as long as the user is interacting with the application (until they log out or the session times out).
Spring Scope:
Beans with @Scope("session") are created once per user session and shared across all requests in that session.
Example Use:
Storing user login information, shopping cart contents, or preferences.

Summary Table:

Feature	                     HTTP Request	                 HTTP Session

Lifetime	                 One client-server interaction	 Multiple interactions (user session)
Scope	                     Short (milliseconds/seconds)	 Longer (minutes/hours)
Spring Scope	             @Scope("request")	             @Scope("session")
Use Case	                 Per-request data	             Per-user data across requests


